replies.body:
You said that Riot will not be able to continually audit every service and function (Third-Party Services) for player security? If this statement is true, would you mind enlightening me as to what is the point of blacklisting these apps, only to have them be neglected by the team that is supposedly supposed to be, as you said "auditing" it. Sounds to me like you agree that this is a massive wasted of time and resources on Riots part.

Because I am so naive, would you also care to explain how you plan on blacklisting all these Third-Party Services, yet provide the community with such a vague list as to what is not allowed? Sounds to me like not only is Riot's resource management below a sufficient standard, but so is the communication of it's managing administrators. Would it not be logical, if not to show a black-list then to provide us with a white-list? Or is that too much work for the Riot staff, where they would just rather ban the "problem users"?

When it comes to rules and regulations, Riot needs to come up with a black and white system. Right now all you guys seem to be doing with this issue it muddying the water. Everyone is confused on this topic. You are sending out ban threats with out sufficient information being provide to these users, and on top of that, you are acting like you are solving some major game changing problem when in reality the majority for these app, excluding actual game hacks provide a minuscule and insignificant change to the game. Like I said in my previous post, not only is this a massive waste of time and energy, it is a breach of peoples privacy and moral standings. Rather then fix the game Riot would rather just penalize it's users for automating a manual process that all players have access to. I am mainly talking about MKJOGO. I am more than disappointed with how Riot has chosen to handle this issue.{{champion:21}}
